Project: Upkeep — Maintenance Accountability & Insight System
A web-based system for small property managers (5–50 units) to handle maintenance requests with structured workflows, audit trails, and analytics. Built as a Software Engineering final project using the Iterative and Incremental model.

Tech Stack

Frontend: Flutter (Dart), Flutter Web, go_router for routing, fl_chart for charts
Backend: FastAPI (Python), Pydantic, Uvicorn
Database: PostgreSQL, SQLAlchemy (ORM), Supabase (DB deployment)
Auth: JWT-based
Deployment: Vercel


Roles

Tenant: submits requests, views status, closes ticket at the end
Property Manager: acknowledges, works on, and resolves tickets


5 Ticket States (in order, do not change)

Ticket Opened — by tenant
Problem Acknowledged — by manager
Resolving In Progress — by manager
Problem Resolved — by manager
Ticket Closed — confirmed and closed by tenant

State transitions are enforced at the API level. No skipping states.

Pages by Role
Tenant:

/login
/tenant/dashboard — list of their tickets with status badges, submit button
/tickets/new — submission form: title, description, category, urgency, optional photo
/tickets/[id] — read-only detail, horizontal stepper, audit log, close-ticket modal when status is Problem Resolved

Manager:

/manager/dashboard — all tickets across units, filters by status/unit, summary strip (SLA breaches, unacknowledged)
/manager/tickets/[id] — full detail, next-state-only button, communication log/notes panel, SLA indicator badge
/manager/analytics — avg resolution time, open/closed ratio, monthly trend, tickets per unit, SLA breach count
/manager/units — per-unit overview with recurring issue flags
/manager/units/[unitId] — full ticket history for one unit

Both roles:

/profile — name, email, password change
/manager/settings — configurable SLA thresholds per category


4 Iterations
Iteration 1 — Foundation:

JWT auth, Ticket CRUD, core UI pages
Pages: /login, /tenant/dashboard, /tickets/new, /tickets/[id] (basic), /manager/dashboard (basic), /manager/tickets/[id] (status button, next state only)
Must demo full 5-state lifecycle end-to-end by end of iteration

Iteration 2 — Accountability Logic:

Audit log recording on every state change
Horizontal stepper UI on ticket detail pages
Communication/notes log panel for manager
Tenant close-ticket confirmation modal
State transitions enforced at backend level

Iteration 3 — Insight & SLA:

SLA thresholds per category (e.g. urgent=24hr, normal=72hr)
SLA indicator badge on manager ticket detail
Analytics page with Recharts (use fl_chart in Flutter)
Unit overview and unit detail pages
Recurring issue detection per unit

Iteration 4 — Hardening & Testing:

Unit tests (pytest), integration tests (FastAPI TestClient)
Role restriction checks (manual, from separate accounts)
/manager/settings for configurable SLA thresholds
/profile page for both roles
Final Vercel deployment


UI/UX Design Approach

Design in Figma iteration by iteration, not all upfront
Do a rough low-fidelity sketch of the full system at the start for shared mental model
Full Figma screens only for the iteration you're about to build


Core Flow (finalized)

Tenant submits → manager acknowledges → manager works on it → manager marks resolved → tenant reviews → if satisfied: closes ticket; if not: loops back to Resolving In Progress on manager side